{"id":"2105.02768","submitter":"John Hopfensperger","authors":"John Hopfensperger","title":"Topological Invariant Means on Locally Compact Groups","comments":"The author's PhD thesis. Three chapters are derived from previously\n  published papers. v2: Corrected typos","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Suppose $G$ is an amenable locally compact group. If $\\{F_\\gamma\\} =\n\\{F_\\gamma\\}_{\\gamma\\in\\Gamma}$ is a F\\o{}lner net for $G$, associate it with\nthe net $\\{\\chi_{F_\\gamma} / |F_\\gamma|\\} \\subset L_1(G) \\subset\nL_\\infty^*(G)$. Thus, every accumulation point of $\\{F_\\gamma\\}$ is a\ntopological left-invariant mean on $G$. The following are examples of results\nproved in the present thesis:\n  (1) There exists a F\\o{}lner net which has as its accumulation points a set\nof $2^{2^{\\kappa}}$ distinct topological left-invariant means on $G$, where\n$\\kappa$ is the smallest cardinality of a covering of $G$ by compact subsets.\n  (2) If $G$ is unimodular and $\\mu$ is a topological left-invariant mean on\n$G$, there exists a F\\o{}lner net which has $\\mu$ as its unique accumulation\npoint.\n  (3) Suppose $L \\subset G$ is a lattice subgroup. There is a natural bijection\nof the left-invariant means on $L$ with the topological left-invariant means on\n$G$ if and only if $G/L$ is compact.\n  (4) Every topological left-invariant mean on $G$ is also topological\nright-invariant if and only if $G$ has precompact conjugacy classes.\n  These results lie at the intersection of functional analysis with general\ntopology. Problems in this area can often be solved with standard tools when\n$G$ is $\\sigma$-compact or metrizable, but require more interesting arguments\nin the general case.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 May 2021 15:43:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 16 May 2021 03:56:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-18"}
